Herodotean Life of Homer: While he was spending the winter in Samos, every new moon he visited the most prosperous houses in the island and received gifts in return for singing the following lines, which are called the Ew‘resz‘on& ; he was invariably accompanied by some of the children of the people of the district, who led him about:

We are come for aid to the house of a great man, a man great in power, and loud of voice like one ever in prosperity. Open of thyself, good door, foi-much wealth enters by thee, and with the wealth abundant good cheer and goodly peace.
